      <article class="post-content">

        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p><strong>Domain age</strong> is the length of time a domain name has been registered with an accredited registrar and actively used on the web. Google has confirmed it is <strong>not a direct ranking factor</strong> &mdash; John Mueller has repeated this on multiple occasions since 2019. However, older domains often outrank new ones because they have accumulated the things Google actually ranks: backlinks, content depth, brand mentions, and trust signals.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Direct ranking factor?</div>
            <div class="tms-value">No (Google confirmed)</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Technical SEO</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Correlates with rankings</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Yes (indirect)</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Beginner</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">Domain age is the SEO topic most riddled with myth. Every founder buying a new domain wonders if they are starting in a hole, and every aged-domain marketplace claims their inventory carries invisible ranking power. The truth sits somewhere between "it does not matter" and "it obviously does" &mdash; and it is worth understanding precisely why.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is domain age?</h2>
        <p>Domain age typically has two meanings, and it matters which one you mean:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Registration age</strong> &mdash; how long ago the domain was first registered with a registrar (visible in WHOIS).</li>
          <li><strong>Indexed age</strong> &mdash; how long the domain has been active with real content indexed by Google (visible via the Wayback Machine or first Search Console impression).</li>
        </ul>
        <p>Registered-but-parked domains do not accumulate SEO value. A 20-year-old domain that has been parked its whole life has virtually the same SEO footprint as one registered today. Indexed age is what actually correlates with performance.</p>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">Google&rsquo;s stance</div>
          <p>Google&rsquo;s John Mueller has publicly stated that <strong>"domain age helps nothing"</strong> as a direct ranking factor. Search Engine Journal covered his 2019 X post and Mueller has repeated the position in Search Console office hours ever since. The correlation you see in data is entirely proxy for other things.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why domain age (indirectly) matters</h2>
        <p>Google does not weight the age number, but time compounds three things Google absolutely does weight:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Backlink accumulation.</strong> A 10-year-old domain with steady publishing has had a decade to earn dofollow links. A new domain starts at zero and has to build up.</li>
          <li><strong>Content depth and topical authority.</strong> Older sites often have hundreds of interlinked pages covering a topic. That depth outranks a 20-page new site even at equivalent content quality.</li>
          <li><strong>Brand and trust signals.</strong> Repeat brand searches, mentions across the web, review platforms &mdash; all take time to build. New domains rarely have any.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How Google actually treats domain age</h2>

        <div class="url-flow">
          <span class="uf-comment"># Google ranking evaluation (simplified)</span><br>
          Rank = f(<span class="uf-label">relevance</span> + <span class="uf-label">quality</span> + <span class="uf-label">backlinks</span> + <span class="uf-label">brand signals</span> + <span class="uf-label">UX</span> + &hellip;)<br>
          <br>
          <span class="uf-comment"># Domain age is NOT a direct input</span><br>
          Domain age &rarr; <span class="uf-status">correlates with</span> backlinks + content + brand<br>
          &rarr; correlation &ne; causation
        </div>

        <h3>The "Google sandbox" myth</h3>
        <p>The idea that Google puts every new domain in a "sandbox" for 6-12 months is <strong>largely myth</strong>. What people call the sandbox is actually the natural time it takes for a new site to accumulate the backlinks, content, and engagement that competitive rankings require. Low-competition long-tail keywords rank within weeks on new domains.</p>

        <h2 id="types">Aged domain vs new domain</h2>

        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr><th>Attribute</th><th>New domain</th><th>Aged clean domain</th><th>Aged expired domain</th></tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr><td><strong>Starting backlinks</strong></td><td class="cell-no">Zero</td><td class="cell-yes">Inherited</td><td class="cell-meh">Inherited (partial decay)</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Content history</strong></td><td class="cell-no">None</td><td class="cell-yes">Full archive</td><td class="cell-meh">May conflict</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Trust signals</strong></td><td class="cell-no">None</td><td class="cell-yes">Established</td><td class="cell-meh">Variable</td></tr>
              <tr class="row-highlight"><td><strong>Speed to rank</strong></td><td>6-12 months</td><td class="cell-yes">Immediate lift</td><td class="cell-meh">Depends on history</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Penalty risk</strong></td><td class="cell-yes">None</td><td class="cell-yes">Low</td><td class="cell-no">High (inherited)</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <h2 id="examples">Real domain age examples</h2>

        <h3>1. Startup on a fresh domain</h3>
        <p>A SaaS launches on a brand-new .com. First 6 months: rankings for long-tail branded queries only. Months 6-12: category head terms start to appear on pages 3-5. Month 12-18: consistent publishing plus 20-50 quality dofollow links push targeted terms to page 1.</p>

        <h3>2. Domain migration to an aged registered brand</h3>
        <p>A company acquires a competitor with a 15-year-old domain and migrates their content there via 301 redirects. Result: rankings often lift within weeks because the acquired domain&rsquo;s backlink profile and trust signals are inherited.</p>

        <h3>3. Expired-domain rebuild (proceed with caution)</h3>
        <p>An SEO buys an expired domain that used to be a running blog with 500 dofollow links. If Google detects the topical mismatch (old blog was cooking, new site is B2B SaaS), the equity does not transfer cleanly and rankings never materialise.</p>

        <h3>4. Aged but dormant domain</h3>
        <p>Someone activates a domain they registered in 2010 but never used. The domain is 15 years old on WHOIS but effectively new to Google. It ranks like a fresh domain.</p>

        <h2 id="vs-related">Domain age vs domain authority &mdash; how they differ</h2>
        <p>Both correlate with SEO strength, but they measure different things.</p>

        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Domain age tells you</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>When the domain was first registered</li>
              <li>How much time the site has had to earn signals</li>
              <li>A rough proxy for accumulated brand history</li>
              <li>Whether the domain predates recent algorithm eras</li>
              <li>A yes/no answer to "is this a fresh site"</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>Domain authority tells you</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Predicted ranking strength on a 0-100 scale</li>
              <li>Backlink profile quality (Moz&rsquo;s calculation)</li>
              <li>Comparative ranking power vs competitors</li>
              <li>Response to link-earning campaigns over time</li>
              <li>Whether the site is genuinely powerful right now</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">7 best practices around domain age</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Do not obsess over the WHOIS date.</strong> The number itself does nothing for ranking. Focus on what compounds with time: content, links, brand.</li>
          <li><strong>Register early, even before launch.</strong> Get the domain live with a simple placeholder or coming-soon page as soon as you know the brand. Google starts recording signals from indexing, not registration.</li>
          <li><strong>Publish consistently from day one.</strong> A new domain with 100 quality pages in 12 months out-ranks a 5-year-old domain with 20 stale pages.</li>
          <li><strong>Earn backlinks steadily.</strong> Steady link growth over months outperforms a big burst that stops.</li>
          <li><strong>If buying an aged domain, audit history carefully.</strong> Check WHOIS history, Wayback Machine archives, Google Search Console access, and any spam / penalty flags.</li>
          <li><strong>Avoid expired domains with topical mismatch.</strong> A cooking blog does not transfer equity cleanly to a B2B SaaS.</li>
          <li><strong>Renew for multiple years.</strong> Long renewal signals commitment. Google has never confirmed weighting it, but it is a low-cost signal to send.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common mistake &mdash; buying domains for "SEO age"</div>
          <p>The aged-domain marketplace industry oversells the value of registration date. What you are actually paying for is inherited backlinks and content history. Verify both with tools like Ahrefs (link profile) and Wayback Machine (content history) before spending on an aged domain.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common domain age mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Assuming new domains cannot rank</strong> &mdash; they can, and often do on long-tail terms within weeks.</li>
          <li><strong>Paying premium for old-but-parked domains</strong> &mdash; registration age without activity buys you nothing.</li>
          <li><strong>Migrating to an unrelated aged domain</strong> &mdash; equity does not transfer through topical mismatch.</li>
          <li><strong>Treating age as a defensive moat</strong> &mdash; old sites that stop publishing get outranked by newer, sharper competitors.</li>
          <li><strong>Ignoring the Wayback Machine when buying</strong> &mdash; you might inherit a spam site&rsquo;s history without realising.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="how-thestacc-helps">How theStacc helps new domains rank faster</h2>
        <p>The gap between "new domain" and "ranking domain" is not time &mdash; it is unfocused execution. theStacc builds a launch-phase SEO plan that compresses the 12-month ramp: which topical clusters to publish first, which internal links to build, which quality backlinks are realistic to earn in the first 6 months, and which competitor gaps a new domain can exploit while incumbents ignore them.</p>

        <h2 id="faq">Frequently asked questions</h2>
